<div id="review_2918556973" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2918556973" />
    <a title="Julian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/88864053-julian"><img alt="Julian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563889770p2/88864053.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2918556973?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julian" href="/user/show/88864053-julian">Julian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/36514906-be-with">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2918556973" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer915946174523236613">Idk I know this is a harsh rating and I’m not sure that I mean it. My reasoning behind the 2 stars is in large part because I just didn’t get these poems. They were very hard for me to comprehend initially much less process and I think they would continue to be inaccessible until the author or some other translator provided an analysis. <br/><br/>I also struggled a bit with the border poetry, finding the places that the author chose to use Spanish more gimmicky than holding much literary weight. <br/><br/>I appreci</span>
  <span id="freeText915946174523236613" style="display:none">Idk I know this is a harsh rating and I’m not sure that I mean it. My reasoning behind the 2 stars is in large part because I just didn’t get these poems. They were very hard for me to comprehend initially much less process and I think they would continue to be inaccessible until the author or some other translator provided an analysis. <br /><br />I also struggled a bit with the border poetry, finding the places that the author chose to use Spanish more gimmicky than holding much literary weight. <br /><br />I appreciated the first few poems, which did feel more grounded in what I read of the authors experience following his partners sudden death. This has me wondering if poetry is better (for me at least) if it’s more accessible or at least if an explanation of the authors background is provided. Otherwise, the jumbling of pretty words in pretty form feels strained. <br /><br />When I write poetry I think I often attempt to do something similar: that is, write in some elusive, nondescript way with words I wouldn’t normally use to express myself in an attempt to creatify whatever emotion it is that I’m trying to process. But sometimes this is lost on others beyond myself and the poetry is only ‘good’ poetry to me because I’m the only one able to decipher its labyrinthine meanings. <br /><br />The final thing I’m wondering in relationship to this collection ATM is if contemporary poetry must be so steeped in tragedy to be well regarded. I’m generally more interested in quotidian and shared experience when I read, or at least the ways in which I as an outsider might read from different experiences and try to understand their meanings. There seems to me, however, to be an air of competitiveness (or dare I say pretentiousness) that’s pervasive in a body of work such as this, which only further distances me from its content. <br /><br />Perhaps I will revisit upon further study, but these are my thoughts today. </span>
  <a data-text-id="915946174523236613" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


