<span id="freeTextContainer13976740880569634782">&quot;The voice singing in the kitchen[ ]isn&apos;t your voice<br/>There is[ ]no voice singing in the kitchen<br/><br/>Open last night&apos;s[ ]pizza box<br/>Its dry[ ]strings of cheese splayed<br/>Like tendons[ ]in a crushed hand&quot;<br/><br/>(brackets added by me to attempt to indicate large gaps in each line)<br/><br/>One way Forrest Gander echoes the experience of absence in this elegiac collection is through his use of form. Many lines are fractured in some way. At times, short stanzas sit alone on their top or bottom half of the page.<br/><br/>When the beloved </span>
  <span id="freeText13976740880569634782" style="display:none">"The voice singing in the kitchen[ ]isn't your voice<br />There is[ ]no voice singing in the kitchen<br /><br />Open last night's[ ]pizza box<br />Its dry[ ]strings of cheese splayed<br />Like tendons[ ]in a crushed hand"<br /><br />(brackets added by me to attempt to indicate large gaps in each line)<br /><br />One way Forrest Gander echoes the experience of absence in this elegiac collection is through his use of form. Many lines are fractured in some way. At times, short stanzas sit alone on their top or bottom half of the page.<br /><br />When the beloved is another poet (in this case the inimitable C.D. Wright), whose voice the reader may know well and whose loss the reader may also be mourning, the elegiac work takes on a heightened poignancy. <br /><br />Even not knowing Wright's work, the reader can observe Gander using all of the tools at his disposal, figuration, form, translation, the scientific language of ecopoetics, to find avenues of expression which will inevitably fall short of the fullest expression of emotion, but in doing so acquire deep resonance in the reader.<br /><br />The collection does not falsely end in resolution. The final lines from the last segment of "Littoral Zone" (which dialogue with the photography of Michael Flomen) twist together the language of ecopoetics and loss in a way only this particular poet could:<br /><br /> "...From<br />afar, do you see me now<br />briefly here in this phantasmic<br />standoff riding<br />pain's whirlforms?"</span>
  <a data-text-id="13976740880569634782" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


