<div id="review_2626167002" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2626167002" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/556887-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2626167002?book_show_action=true">Dec 14, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/556887-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2626167002" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer48737623335472973">I was really struck by how cool this cover looked, and I remembered, vaguely, really enjoying Core Samples from the World when I read that. This one didn&apos;t tickle me as much, though I&apos;m still glad I read it.<br/><br/>There are two long sequences here that are interesting-- one about migrants at the southern border and another about spending time with his mother and her senile dementia. There are other scattered series, including a series of poems paired with photos of rock formations in caves. The thing h</span>
  <span id="freeText48737623335472973" style="display:none">I was really struck by how cool this cover looked, and I remembered, vaguely, really enjoying Core Samples from the World when I read that. This one didn't tickle me as much, though I'm still glad I read it.<br /><br />There are two long sequences here that are interesting-- one about migrants at the southern border and another about spending time with his mother and her senile dementia. There are other scattered series, including a series of poems paired with photos of rock formations in caves. The thing holding all this together is Gander's language and style-- his lexicon incorporates a lot of technical/ theoretical language that left me scrambling for a dictionary. It's not like this never happens, but it usually doesn't happen when I'm reading poems; Gander's language is very professorial and indented to what I think is Continental philosophy. For me, it made the emotional impact of the poems feel a little attenuated, but I'm sure there are people for whom this is really exciting and bracing.<br /><br />Gander's lines go all over the place. He likes to range, intellectually and otherwise, and there's an openness to his style. It's solid, accomplished stuff, just not totally to my taste this time around. </span>
  <a data-text-id="48737623335472973" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


