    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3149377043" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3149377043" />
    <a title="Garron" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7220361-garron"><img alt="Garron" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609522000p2/7220361.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3149377043?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Garron" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Garron" href="/user/show/7220361-garron">Garron</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3149377043" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17450581809567375768">The hardship of the artist is not creating but conveying. How does one choose the right words to convey grief, loss, regret? Not merely to recant them, but to create an empathic shared space where these emotions are just as real to the viewer as they are to the artist. Furthermore, to do it in such a way that does not take away from the subject matter, especially when it is one as important or vivid as the speaker’s own flesh and blood, their mother, is impossible for most of us. <br/><br/>In Be With, Gan</span>
  <span id="freeText17450581809567375768" style="display:none">The hardship of the artist is not creating but conveying. How does one choose the right words to convey grief, loss, regret? Not merely to recant them, but to create an empathic shared space where these emotions are just as real to the viewer as they are to the artist. Furthermore, to do it in such a way that does not take away from the subject matter, especially when it is one as important or vivid as the speaker’s own flesh and blood, their mother, is impossible for most of us. <br /><br />In Be With, Gander successfully rides the line between these issues and comes out with a furious, raw, and gentle collection of poetry whose words dance across the page in reflection of their own difficult task: to create meaning and feeling within each of us, its readers. Gander’s vocabulary is incredible, and yet it does not feel out of place. Each word is posited with care and grace in exactly the place it needs to be. This is a 5/5 collection of poetry, and I would strongly recommend it to any lover of words or art. <br /><br />Be wary though, as noted by others, this book does bring out many strong feelings, especially the poem “Ruth.” It was a long time since a poem was a catalyst for tears, but “Ruth” brought that wall back down, no, it smashed it wide open. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17450581809567375768" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


