  <span id="freeText15102558794448645686" style="display:none">One of the densest collections I've ever read (and the consistent use of Spanish didn't help in this regard). I was impressed w/ how cohesive it all was (revolving around grief). Will still need to return to this in the future, but everything w/ which i developed some semblance of understanding i found just so damn beautiful. Also I think it'd be impossible to read "Ruth" and not tear up at least a little<br /><br />Peoms i especially liked: Son, Beckoned, Ruth, Carbonized Forest, What It Sounds Like, Where Once a Solid House, Tell Them No<br /><br />Misc. Excerpts<br />"Why // say anything about death, inevitability, how / the body comes to deploy the myriad worm // as if it were a manageable concept not / searing exquisite singularity."<br /><br />"When you asked for less / rigor more entenderment /When you asked / for more-- // _Knowing_: not as recitation / but as / the unhinging / somatic event"<br /><br />"in this / too might be seen / a figuration / of the human, / another intimately / lethal gesture of our / common existence."<br /><br /></span>
