    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2788477841" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2788477841" />
    <a title="Jake Phillips" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76747076-jake-phillips"><img alt="Jake Phillips" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521909945p2/76747076.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2788477841?book_show_action=true">May 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jake Phillips" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jake Phillips" href="/user/show/76747076-jake-phillips">Jake Phillips</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2788477841" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14558660131760939657">My complicated feelings toward this collection mirror the complexities of the poems themselves, I suppose. The language is eclectic, incredibly elevated (e.g. &quot;levorotatory isomers&quot;) and often very abstract; it has the potential to alienate even well-learned readers. Despite some difficulties in reading, there are plenty of beautiful moments, both in the language itself and the images created by it. The star of the show was, for me, &quot;Ruth&quot;, a gorgeous, extended, and unimpeded poem about Gander&apos;s</span>
  <span id="freeText14558660131760939657" style="display:none">My complicated feelings toward this collection mirror the complexities of the poems themselves, I suppose. The language is eclectic, incredibly elevated (e.g. "levorotatory isomers") and often very abstract; it has the potential to alienate even well-learned readers. Despite some difficulties in reading, there are plenty of beautiful moments, both in the language itself and the images created by it. The star of the show was, for me, "Ruth", a gorgeous, extended, and unimpeded poem about Gander's relationship with his mother and her decaying mind. This piece, above all others in the collection, avoids being hindered by unusual or elusive diction to deliver a poignant relationship to the reader.<br /><br />While I wouldn't say this collection is one of my favorites, I do feel as if I learned something-- maybe even grew, a little-- while reading it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14558660131760939657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


